990. Quid tu ais? ‘and you, what do you say to this2' The tu has a certain emphasis, so sean quid tzZ α- as a dactyl. The phrase is similarly used in v, 627, where Hegio turns from Aristophontes to ask Tyndarus what he in his turn has to say on the matter. Often however quid tu ais merely expresses wondering surprise, like our ‘what !‚' e. g. v. 289. Ipsus, the emphatic form of ipse, is normal in phrases of this type, e. g.
